Section 1:
1 L.D. 1270
2 Date: (Filing No. H- )
4 STATE OF MAINE
5 HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
6 132ND LEGISLATURE
7 FIRST SPECIAL SESSION
8 HOUSE AMENDMENT “ ” to COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “A” to H.P. 845,
9 L.D. 1270, “An Act to Establish the Department of Energy Resources”
10 Amend the amendment on page 1 by inserting after paragraph B the following:
11 'Amend the bill in Part A by inserting after section 6 the following:
12 'Sec. A-7. 26 MRSA §1308, sub-§1, as amended by PL 2023, c. 333, §1, is further
13 amended to read:
14 1. Determination of wage and benefits rates. The Bureau of Labor Standards shall
15 investigate and determine the prevailing hourly wage and benefits rate paid in the
16 construction industry in this State. To determine the prevailing hourly wage and benefits
17 rate, the bureau shall:
18 A. Collect a set of data by conducting a survey of wages and benefits during the 2nd
19 and 3rd week of July of each year;
20 B. Collect a 2nd set of data through certified payroll submissions on state construction
21 of public works during the 2nd and 3rd week of July of each year from any state agency
22 that contracts for the construction of public works; and
23 C. Collect a 3rd set of data for the job classification under the federal Davis-Bacon
24 Act.
25 Survey data collected pursuant to paragraph A and certified payroll data collected pursuant
26 to paragraph B must be submitted to the bureau by the 2nd week of October. Each year,
27 labor unions shall submit the most recent collectively bargained rates to the bureau.
28 The bureau shall use the highest wage and benefits information of the 3 data sets collected
29 pursuant to paragraphs A, B and C to determine the prevailing hourly wage and benefits
30 rate. The bureau may also use wage and benefits information received from construction
31 trade associations in its determination of prevailing rates. In determining the prevailing
32 rate, the bureau may ascertain and consider the applicable wage and benefits rates
33 established by collective bargaining agreements, if any, and those rates that are paid
34 generally in the locality where the construction of the public works is to be performed. For
35 any classification, if that rate represents a decrease from the prevailing hourly wage and
36 benefits rate as published in the immediately preceding year, the bureau shall adjust the
37 rate to ensure that the decrease is not more than 15%.
Page 1 - 132LR1752(03)
HOUSE AMENDMENT
HOUSE AMENDMENT “ ” to COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “A” to H.P. 845, L.D. 1270
1 The bureau shall ascertain and consider wage and benefits information received from
2 construction trade associations and labor unions that are paid generally in the locality where
3 the construction of the public works is to be performed in its determination of prevailing
4 rates.
5 For purposes of this subsection, "benefits" means health and welfare contributions, pension
6 or individual retirement account contributions and vacation and annuity contributions, per
7 diem in lieu of wages and any other form of payment, except for wages, made to or on
8 behalf of the employee. If a defined contribution amount is not established, the most
9 accurate estimated value of contributions must be included.' '
10 Amend the amendment by striking out all of section A-10.
11 Amend the bill in §10313 by striking out all of subsection 5 (page 10, lines 38 to 43
12 and page 11, lines 1 to 5 in amendment) and inserting the following:
13 '5. Wage, safety and apprenticeship standards. If the department selects a project
14 for a contract for energy from an assisted project located in the State as defined in Title 26,
15 section 1304, subsection 1-A, the department shall ensure that standards under the contract
16 applicable to contractors and subcontractors involved in the project's construction include
17 requirements that a contractor or subcontractor:
18 A. Ensure that all construction workers earn compensation at or above the prevailing
19 hourly wage as described in Title 26, section 1308; and
20 B. Meet the requirements described in Title 26, sections 1301, 1317 and 3502.'
21 Amend the amendment by inserting after section A-13 the following:
22 'Sec. A-14. Wage and benefit report. By January 15, 2026, the Department of
23 Labor shall submit a report to the Joint Standing Committee on Labor that includes
24 information detailing the process and progress to date of how the Department of Labor,
25 Bureau of Labor Standards is using the wage and benefits information received from
26 construction trade associations and labor unions in its determination of prevailing rates
27 pursuant to the Maine Revised Statutes, Title 26, section 1308, subsection 1. The joint
28 standing committee may report out a bill based on the report to the Second Regular Session
29 of the 132nd Legislature.'
30 Amend the amendment by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or
31 section number to read consecutively.
32 SUMMARY
3333 This amendment amends Committee Amendment "A" in the following ways. It
3344 removes the changes to the definition of "Maine emerging industry compensation
3355 threshold." It replaces the requirement that the Department of Energy Resources ensure
3366 that community and workforce enhancement standards meet certain criteria with a
3377 requirement related to wage, safety and apprenticeship standards. It amends the provisions
3388 in the Maine Revised Statutes that provide the process for how the Bureau of Labor
3399 Standards within the Department of Labor is required to determine the prevailing hourly
Page 2 - 132LR1752(03)
HOUSE AMENDMENT
HOUSE AMENDMENT “ ” to COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “A” to H.P. 845, L.D. 1270
410 wage and benefits rate paid in the construction industry and requires the department to
421 submit a report detailing the process to the Joint Standing Committee on Labor.
432 SPONSORED BY: ___________________________________
443 (Representative RUNTE, W.)
454 TOWN: York
